Heart Disease: Predicting Presence of Heart Disease

Reading the file

disease <- read.csv("/Users/Esteban/Downloads/heartdisease1.csv")
attach(disease)

Data Cleaning

sapply(disease, typeof)
##          age          sex           cp     trestbps         chol          fbs 
##    "integer"    "integer"    "integer"    "integer"    "integer"    "integer" 
##      restecg      thalach        exang      oldpeak        slope           ca 
##    "integer"    "integer"    "integer"     "double"    "integer"    "integer"

We know from the UCI Machine Learning Repository that in the data set features 1, 4, 5, 8, and 10 are numerical. We will keep the values as is, as some of them like age for example, are supposed to be integers and not doubles.

Quantitative Data

We will now replace the NA values with the mean imputation of each feature.

disease$age[is.na(disease$age)] <- mean(disease$age,na.rm=TRUE) # 1
disease$trestbps[is.na(disease$trestbps)] <- mean(disease$trestbps,na.rm=TRUE) # 4
disease$chol[is.na(disease$chol)] <- mean(disease$chol,na.rm=TRUE) # 5
disease$thalach[is.na(disease$thalach)] <- mean(disease$thalach,na.rm=TRUE) # 8
disease$oldpeak[is.na(disease$oldpeak)] <- mean(disease$oldpeak,na.rm=TRUE) # 10

Check for any NA in the six numerical features

ind <- c(1,4,5,8,10)

for (i in ind){
  print(anyNA(disease[,i]))
}

Qualitative Data

We know from the UCI Machine Learning Repository that 3, 7, 11, 12, 13, and 14 are categorical features. We also know that 2, 6, 9, and 14 are supposed to be binary.

First we want to remove any NA qualitative observations.

dim(na.omit(disease))
## [1] 145  14
disease <- na.omit(disease)

Notice that the amount of observations decreased significantly.

Now we will turn the qualitative features into factors, in R we do not need to perform OHE (One Hot Encoding) if we do this.

ind <- c(2,3,6,7,9,11,12,13,14)

for (i in ind){
  disease[,i] <- as.factor(disease[,i])
  print(levels(disease[,i]))
}

Now split the data into training and testing sets, using a 70-30 split.

set.seed(4052)
test.ind <- sample(nrow(disease), floor(nrow(disease)*0.3))

train <- disease[-test.ind,]
test <- disease[test.ind,]

Now that we can build the training model removing the unnecessary features.

# Final model (Build using training set)
log.model <- glm(heartdisease~. -slope -chol -age -fbs -oldpeak -exang, data = train, family = binomial)

We will now build the testing model for logistic regression.

# Predicted probability of being in class
log.pred <- predict(log.model, newdata = test, type = "response") 
log.class <- as.numeric(log.pred > 0.5)

# Confusion Matrix
(mat <- xtabs(~log.class + test$heartdisease))

A error rate of about 0.1636

ROC curve and AUC

set.seed(1)
log.pred <- predict(log.model, newdata = test)
pred <- prediction(predictions = log.pred, labels = test$heartdisease)

# ROC Curve
log.roc <- performance(pred, measure = "tpr", x.measure = "fpr")
plot(log.roc, main = "Logistic ROC")

We can see that the the ROC curve looks pretty good, maybe we could have gotten better results if we performed cross validation instead of a train-test split but for now this is ok.

log_perf2 <- performance(pred, measure = "auc")
log_perf2@y.values[[1]]
## [1] 0.9298246

The AUC is about 0.8787.

Random Forest

We will use k-fold cross validation for the random forest method. For random forest the only hyperparameters we want to tune is the number of trees(ntree), and the number of features to use per split (n).

p <- ncol(train) - 1
k <- 5
ntree <- c(100, 200, 300, 400, 500, 600, 700, 800, 900, 1000)

n <- 1:p 
tuningpar <- expand.grid(n, ntree)
cv.er.forest <- matrix(nrow = k, ncol = nrow(tuningpar))

Cross Validation K-Fold Split

set.seed(1)
obs.per.fold <- ceiling(nrow(train)/k)
shuffle.indices <- sample(nrow(train), nrow(train))
folds <- vector("list", length = k)
for (i in 1:k) {
  if (i != k) { 
    fold.indices <- (i - 1)*obs.per.fold + 1:obs.per.fold
    folds[[i]] <- shuffle.indices[fold.indices]
  } else {
    fold.indices <- ((i - 1)*obs.per.fold + 1):nrow(train)
    folds[[i]] <- shuffle.indices[fold.indices]
  }
}

Testing for the two hyper parameters, ntrees && mtry.

set.seed(1)
for (i in 1:k) {
  cv.training <- train[-folds[[i]],]
  cv.validation <- train[folds[[i]],]
    for (j in 1:nrow(tuningpar)) {
      rf <- randomForest(x = cv.training[,-11], y = cv.training[,11], mtry = tuningpar[j,1],
      ntree = tuningpar[j,2])
      rfpred <- predict(rf, newdata = cv.validation[,-11])
      cv.er.forest[i,j] <- mean(rfpred != cv.validation[,11])
    }
}
meancv <- colMeans(cv.er.forest)
optimal <- tuningpar[which(meancv == min(meancv)),]
names(optimal) <- c("# of Parameters", "# of Trees")
optimal
##    # of Parameters # of Trees
## 54               2        500

Found that 1000 trees and 2 parameters per split optimizes the randomforest model.

ROC for SVM

#Create the function
rocplot<-function(predi,truth,...){
predob<-prediction(predi,truth)
perf<-performance(predob,"tpr","fpr")
plot(perf,...)
}
# Obtain the fitted values
svm.fit <- svm(heartdisease~., data = train, kernel = "linear", degree = 1, cost = 10, decision.values=TRUE)
fitted <- attributes(predict(svm.fit, newdata = test, decision.values=TRUE))$decision.values
rocplot(-fitted, test$heartdisease, main = "Support Vector Machine (Poly) ROC")

AUC for SVM

svm.fit <- svm(heartdisease~., data = train, kernel = "linear", degree = 1, cost = 10, probability=TRUE)
prob <- attributes(predict(svm.fit, newdata = test, probability =TRUE))$probabilities[,2]

predictionsvm <- prediction(prob,test$heartdisease)
svm_perf2 <- performance(predictionsvm, measure = "auc")

Random Forest Iterative Regression Imputation

p <- ncol(train) - 1
k <- 5
ntree <- c(100, 200, 300, 400, 500, 600, 700, 800, 900, 1000)

n <- 1:p 
tuningpar <- expand.grid(n, ntree)
cv.er.forest <- matrix(nrow = k, ncol = nrow(tuningpar))

Cross Validation K-Fold Split

set.seed(1)
obs.per.fold <- ceiling(nrow(train)/k)
shuffle.indices <- sample(nrow(train), nrow(train))
folds <- vector("list", length = k)
for (i in 1:k) {
  if (i != k) { 
    fold.indices <- (i - 1)*obs.per.fold + 1:obs.per.fold
    folds[[i]] <- shuffle.indices[fold.indices]
  } else {
    fold.indices <- ((i - 1)*obs.per.fold + 1):nrow(train)
    folds[[i]] <- shuffle.indices[fold.indices]
  }
}

Testing for the two hyper parameters, ntrees && mtry.

set.seed(1)
for (i in 1:k) {
  cv.training <- train[-folds[[i]],]
  cv.validation <- train[folds[[i]],]
    for (j in 1:nrow(tuningpar)) {
      rf <- randomForest(x = cv.training[,-14], y = cv.training[,14], mtry = tuningpar[j,1],
      ntree = tuningpar[j,2])
      rfpred <- predict(rf, newdata = cv.validation[,-14])
      cv.er.forest[i,j] <- mean(rfpred != cv.validation[,14])
    }
}
meancv <- colMeans(cv.er.forest)
optimal <- tuningpar[which(meancv == min(meancv)),]
names(optimal) <- c("# of var sampled", "# of Trees")
optimal
##    # of var sampled # of Trees
## 4                 4        100
## 27                1        300

ROC for Support Vector Machine

#Create the function
rocplot<-function(predi,truth,...){
predob<-prediction(predi,truth)
perf<-performance(predob,"tpr","fpr")
plot(perf,...)
}
# Obtain the fitted values
svm.fit <- svm(heartdisease~., data = train, kernel = "polynomial", degree = 1, cost = 1, decision.values=TRUE)
fitted <- attributes(predict(svm.fit, newdata = test, decision.values=TRUE))$decision.values
rocplot(-fitted, test$heartdisease, main = "Support Vector Machine ROC")

predictionsvm <- prediction(prob,test$heartdisease)
